He also confessed to having organized illegal fundraising for former liberal vice-president Nathalie Normandeau.
Sewer contracts whose costs were artificially increased by him
In Montreal, the "system" of corruption worked smoothly.
Former civil engineer Gilles Surprenant described this in detail before the Commission: in ten years he received gifts from the construction company, invitations to travel, golf tournaments, restaurants and ice hockey games, as well as bribes amounting to 736,000 dollars in return for sewer contracts, whose costs he artificially bloated.
Other road construction officials have admitted that they were lubricated by artificially bloating the bills with false extras by 30-40%.
In addition, an organizer of the Mayor's Party, Martin Dumont, accused Mr Tremblay of deliberately overlooking a shadow budget that filled his coffers with black money.
As a result of these revelations, Mr Tremblay resigned at the beginning of November, which plunged Montreal into a severe crisis.
Chantal Rouleau was one of the first Montreal MPs to sound the alarm.
As mayor of the Rivière-des-Prairies district, in the east of the island, from 2010, she opposed the sale of a municipal property that was purchased for $5 million and resold for 1.6 million to developers in the booming real estate market.
70% black money in election campaigns
Of the investigation that is ultimately being carried out, she says that she "pulls on a thread that allows us to understand the functioning of the system underfoot by ants in order to stop the evil and denounce the guilty".
She says that the procedure is "painful but positive".
We are in the process of cleaning up the wound, but we would need an investigation unit intended solely for Montreal, as well as supervision to prevent a return of questionable practices.
How to clean up.
Regularly.
Jacques Duchesneau, for his part, notes that "officials have stolen several hundred million dollars", but is mainly concerned about the role of "mandate carriers who are informed about tactics" if they were not involved in the fraud!
Starting from a 70% black money share in the funding of Quebec's election campaigns, he jokes: "I was told that this was only a weak slip of reality."
The Quebec government proposes to limit donations to parties to $100, which according to him would not change the situation: "Until campaign spending is strictly limited, black money will be in circulation in politics."
He recommends a complete overhaul of the public procurement system and the financing of the parties: "We cannot go deeper; by getting to the bottom of things with courage, we can rebuild the house on a more solid basis with more controls and laws."
If this story damages Quebec's international reputation and Montreal's, Mr Duchesneau calls on those who laugh to take a look into their own backyard...
