A constitution with the crowbar in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever in relation to the Declaration of Constitution, which temporarily grants it unlimited power, he has decided to put everything on a map.
To the surprise of all, he announced on Wednesday that the constitutional assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state granted this plenary two additional months to complete his work.
Egypt has now been relying for almost two years on a provisional, repeatedly amended text, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "steps the right with his feet".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time which forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text to the Egyptians section by section.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining his public and democratic legitimacy, while the protest is raging throughout the country.
After reaffirming in an interview with the American newsreel Time, Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote favorably.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to a hasty vote: "You either vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited authority", the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constituent assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of Liberals have not complied with the call.
Shortly before the Declaration of the Constitution in mid-November, they turned away because they believe that they have not been able to express their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve quorum, 11 alternate members were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles were usually adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only disagreement of the day was expressed in the time of prayer, as some members of the panel thought that the pendulum clock of the Constituent Assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, eventually remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made a stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
The Liberals, who regard this only as a propaganda strike, reply to "failure".
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they have an eye on Article 220, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory role, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to the Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying, because "the persons who are called for an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy at all.
One can see in this the first signs of a theocracy".
Liberal fears are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be much less moderate than the current one.
"There is currently no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics, some of whom have been trained in the French system," appeases Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, that "in relation to Article 220 there may be ambiguity, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, ed.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of dispute: the powers of the army.
In line with the military's wish, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations in defence of human rights have called for.
The latter also share their fears with regard to the text which they regard as threatening freedom.
The facts of the blasphemy are being upheld, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no more article refers to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In your opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian President had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The proponents of the head of state will march Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five most important reasons for visiting Israel.
Bending to the Sacred Places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding celebration, the walking on the water, the breastfeeding of the sea storm and fishing.
It was here that Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
However, most sanctuaries are found in Jerusalem.
Here, believers commit the path of suffering or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands in the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place of the Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes there with wishes that are then fulfilled.
Take a trip to the heights
The ruins of the fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rock face in the mountains at an altitude of 450 metres above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins on their own.
All the others take an air cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, where it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometres.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
Not all of them can be visited on just one trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Quran manuscripts or Dead Sea Scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean desert are preserved, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection of works by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited there.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures by the visitors and bath servants of the time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops there.
Admission is free, and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the monument to the children built to commemorate the 1.5 million children destroyed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
Upon entering the room, there is total darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and of the lands in which they died shall be heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing Something for Health
The three main recreational areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
At each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salinity and thus even carries non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt brine) and medicinal mud as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and for the calming of damaged nerves.
Touching the Mysteries of Antiquity
The old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast, hides these secrets.
Through this city was the famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
According to legend, Fortuna is supposed to be a fixture for all who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries on photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can roam through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
Evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre.
Bookmarks for tourists
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the journey is not taken in euros, but in dollars, which can simply be changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekel).
In the city you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a expressway and in Haifa the only underground line in the country with six stations connecting the lower city with the upper city.
Actually, it's an underground funicular.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which is sufficient including transfer for a trip of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday night to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning, the working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, marine products, fish without scales and food containing both milk and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes with mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls made of pureed beans and peas (Falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-fed cats that roam comfortably and unmolested through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parking cars.
The cats like busy places and don't say no to treats.
A rental car costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the brand.
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, prior to the cancellation of the visa requirement on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already trading with fake certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families left at home.
On 1 December, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to take a test certifying knowledge of the Russian language.
To date, this scheme only applies to migrants wishing to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing sector and in retail trade.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests are to become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
Not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the basics of legislation are required.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both the receipt and extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also excluded from this law are persons who received their certificates and diplomas before the disintegration of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problems and protection of rights
All examination offices will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 centres have been opened in Russia.
The initiative for the introduction of the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Before the law came into force, however, civil rights activists repeatedly asked the following question in the press: What is the point?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring for both the Russians and the guest workers?
Above all, spokesman for the Migration Authority said, the aim was to reduce the number of forced labourers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected even before their departure.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems are encountered by migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical examination.
Sebelew is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who, under the pretext of help, will put him in a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure with dozens of his like months without food and documents and will work 12 to 14 hours a day.
Many complaints from our migrants reach us.
"In your home country you will be promised the one, and on arrival you will be cheated, their passports will be taken away, and you will not receive the promised salary," confirms the head of the Central Administration for Labour Migration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't scold me, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that not only do they not master the language of the target country, but they are also hardly able to express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmens, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As a teenager, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect regarding the law.
Only migrants with legal status have to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no exam and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers continue to reside illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Access forbidden to unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that most of our documents are fake and we are not registered, and that then causes cases of extortion.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," says the Tajike Umed Huschkadamov to journalists.
"Don't worry about the cost of fake papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants can be faked.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get them in vain: every migrant who hoped to avoid the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this costs a migrant three thousand rubles.
Both officials and civil rights activists agree that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be bought easily.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers, who fall through the test the first time, that they will have time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where no active communication with people is necessary.
Interior Ministry ignores illegal weapons market
Excessively low proportion of legal weapons in criminal offences
The Russian Interior Ministry plans to tighten the arms law for private gun owners.
The authorities are thus responding to recent events: injured in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the amok run of Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov.
The police want to ban the wearing of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age of possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by Irina Jarovaja, Chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act would be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to fight the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter was published on the Internet, whose authors - representatives of various gun associations - demand that the authorities refrain from "sensibly tightening up".
The percentage of crimes involving registered weapons is very low, said the criminal lawyer, Vasiliy Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1.168 thousand crimes were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private gun owners will not stop criminals from using themselves on the black market.
At the moment, according to the authors, you can find any weapon for little money in Moscow.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons enter the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, tells a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and on the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts gun orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," says Baranez.
On the second channel are illegal weapons stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen from both the police's armory and directly from law enforcement staff.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
Many military camps often saw explosions.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," the former military officer says.
According to Baranez, the weapons manufacturers also make a contribution to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private armament factories that do not stand up to international competition and therefore squander the weapons under their hands on the black market, for example in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is its own, sometimes artisanal production, as well as a mafia that organizes smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the share of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was written by the Centre for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on weapons portals.
According to investigators, most of the illegal weapons are from the army and legal authorities.
Half of all weapons in the black market were there through the "guilt of those responsible for their work with weapons," the report says.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict zones, 14% are due to theft in weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at a gun store, who does not want to be named, assures us that no one has been buying weapons found in illegal excavations for a long time, as they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get the supplies in an armory.
An ensign buys a weapon, such as a type TT gun.
The weapon is issued and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police, of course, know everything and therefore, if they cannot comply with the crime detection plan, they periodically purchase checks from dealers who offer illegal weapons," the sales advisor adds.
"Like in the luxury store"
Buyers and sellers most often find each other through acquaintances.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone noticed me and suggested to come to the "Begowaja" station, where a person would be waiting for me to take me to a certain place where we could then negotiate the price.
I only learned the price of the gun there
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a gun, I need an acquaintance who has contacts," says the sales advisor. "I have such an acquaintance, but I don't trust him."
There are traders in the markets, but there you have to go and meet with a code like "by Ivan Ivanovich, who lets tell that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I'm even coming to some rings about an acquaintance I trust.
He also delivers the rings to me only because he knows that I don't whistle him.
Newbies are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military member Viktor Baranez tried to buy illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he wrote an article on the subject.
