- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "camera", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the depth of the object.
More cameras could possibly solve the problem...
Or amplify the problem, as more calculations would be necessary.
It would be nice to have a flexible, Kinect-like system in which we could play with different camera inclinations to see how this helps us in the three-dimensional determination of a position.
- If I remember correctly, unlike Google, Microsoft did not present its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that with regard to the application of advanced reality technology in everyday life, glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in the raised hand on the way, but I think this: The greatest variant would be a "changing" extended reality, in which we could switch from glasses to smartphones via a cloud.
The glasses are a personal gadget and their strength lies in it (private only you can see), but at the same time their weakness, because an extended reality with glasses prevents you from working on virtual objects together with others.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is not only accessible to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point out: there is no tangible response!
The hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often speak of extended reality as the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection pad.
She perceives pressure excellently!
However, there are also technologies that are actually aimed at giving the "images in the air" something tangible, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is located creates a feeling that is still so weak at the moment, as if someone was blowing over the hand bales.
There are also bands for the wrist that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, also this is a potential direction.
- Did you try to outsmart the brain?
Make it think that it feels what it should feel when it's seeing something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried yet.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely to make a person physically in a closed room believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms and large spheres.
So far, the brain can only be moderately outsmarted, and there are still many busy years ahead of us.
This is what makes working in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: we are only at the beginning of many topics.
