Birth in Space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth dwellers on board are searching for a replacement planet.
To save mankind, the important question arises of how we can reproduce in weightlessness or on the replacement planet?
I do not think there are many choices.
De facto, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"In other words, Mars and Venus," says the research associate of the Astronomical Sternberg Institute Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, there is a temperature of 500 degrees on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at great altitude or in the orbit of Venus, in space.
The researchers first dealt with the question of reproduction in space in terms of flora.
Experiments with plants were carried out half a century before that.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit did not differ in the least from the terrestrial species.
It followed the breeding of insects, more precisely tiny fruit flies (drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979 quail eggs were sent into space to investigate how weightlessness affects embryo development.
A normal chick develops.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick must find a hold; it must be able to stand on its feet and begin to move," explains the laboratory head of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Vladimir Sychev.
Without a solid underground, the chicks overturned wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely dulled.
The chicks did not react to light and sounds.
Four days later, they just died.
"Two times we had chicks hatched and then set the whole thing up, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sychev notes for the failed experiment with chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be present on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"That was just with the biosatellites, but again it was only a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After the landing, the space rats got offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn out of their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive instinct.
Unlike animals, man could do that in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
Such experiments are not carried out on ethical grounds.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was at Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on earth could have answered the following question: Does it survive space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after that flight?
"After all, no one answered this question," says Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just a year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The father of the child, Andriyan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Sawizkaja, who was in orbit twice and even did work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there is still a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts, where everything went well after long flights and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is, even on flights to orbit," concluded Kosmonaut Valeri Polyakov, a hero of the Soviet Union and a hero of the Russian Federation.
Yet mankind must seek new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravity.
The hydrolaboratory in the preparation center of the cosmonauts is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for working in open space.
The water represents weightlessness.
Although adults feel that water is pleasant, it is a foreign environment, but infants feel that water is a natural element.
It's like the little Ichtyanders are witnessing that life on the land got out of the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in the womb of the mother in the amniotic fluid for about 9 months and the fact that it can easily get used to water.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth until the first swim only two weeks pass.
"This is too little time to forget something," says baby swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
While weightlessness is a much more natural condition for a newborn child, the woman does not survive without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles recover enormously quickly and thus also decrease the ability to squeeze out the child.
All right, let's avoid this with birth-making aids.
For example, birth could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze the child out.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Valeri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the gravity, the organism cannot train the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put into a strain suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply lack what is of fundamental importance for his life.
"This experiment, which we are undertaking together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the birth of a disabled person, a completely unadapted person," predicts the head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Igor Pestov.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
At some point, however, it becomes a reality when the Earth's inhabitants in their spaceships set off to a distant planet that will be home to their Earth-born offspring.
NKÚ chief: Control of the black system fails due to political faults
The Czech Republic has good supervisory authorities and adequate laws in connection with public contracts, but falls behind in their application.
In a conversation for Aktuálně.cz, the Vice-President of the Supreme Control Office (Nejvyḥ kontrolní ḥad, NKÚ), Miloslav Kala, says this.
"A law is never perfect, but it must be properly applied - and I do not think this is the case with us," Kala comments on the current situation.
A similar result appears to be a joint control by Czech and German auditors.
As a negative practical example, he cites Prime Minister Petr Nečas' attitude to the so-called "black system".
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls - is the system now banned or allowed?
"A law must be valid, and if something is prohibited by law, then it is not just the head of the government who can come, and the control office, whose duty is to monitor compliance with the law, can hinder its activities," Kala notes.
At the meeting of the Supervisory Committee of the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a common Czech-German project in which the laws of both countries concerning public contracts were compared.
What exactly was that all about?
This is a parallel test that we started about two years ago.
To put it simply, it is a question of the European legislative authority laying down how public contracts are to be handled, and that is what national legislation is building on, and finally, there is the actual practical application.
We have compared all of this with each other, and although the test has not yet been completed, we have been able to see very interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws are perhaps even more "strict and perfect" for us, but the actual application is better in Germany in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to lay down new and more precise rules over and over again, and we also have to deal with the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What does this project mean to you?
It is precisely such joint control that could help us stop constantly trying to perfect laws and reduce and balance thresholds if this does not appear to have a particularly positive effect.
Economic efficiency means acquiring a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But lowering thresholds for contracts does not guarantee that we will achieve this objective.
Perhaps it is even the case that in this way we are only burdening the system with excessive paperwork, and those who are looking for gaps in the system have much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds remained higher.
You are talking about the problems in the practical implementation of the Czech Procurement Act.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar authority here to our NKÚ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ is the Federal Court of Auditors, which is structured in a similar way to ours and also has a college which is only slightly different. However, in principle both authorities work in a similar way.
The competences are also to a certain extent comparable, although Germany is a federal state, i.e. there are also these accounting offices in the individual federal states - in this the German system differs from ours.
The BRH can only control federal funds, which corresponds to our state resources.
Public funds, which are managed by the districts and municipalities, are subject to the control of the state accounting courts.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would hate to compare this without specific information. Nevertheless, Germany is often referred to as an example in some respects, but one certainly cannot say that Germany is better in everything.
Is that because the examiners are better there?
Certainly not, but as I said, I do not like such comparisons.
It should also be noted that those countries that are a model for us also face problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have anything of cooperation with our authority, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what was the importance for your authority of amending the Procurement Act, do you already feel any impact?
In view of the fact that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had any effect on our tests.
Since our controls are carried out retrospectively, there is a certain delay to be expected.
So far, we have had an impact rather in the preparatory phase of future controls - we have introduced the new control instrument "recognition of risks of inefficiency" and with this we have examined and analysed almost 14,000 public contracts - the changes will of course have an impact here as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you see the adoption of this law rather positive, or will the system be burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
