Šimon Ornest: We want to gather positive energy at our concerts
What do you think about the end of the world in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports that we people so much like to jump on.
With our band The Tap Tap, we rather make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
It's a nationwide benefit event that we've been planning for two years.
We want to use the marketing potential of the Maya calendar, which is forecast to end on December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, i.e. on 20 December, three concerts will take place in Prague, Brno and Ostrava at the same time from 21:00.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be about the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is 12 hours ahead of us in a time zone.
Who gave you this idea?
Originally probably from me, afterwards we designed the idea together with our graphic artist Honza Augusta.
Not only do we want to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think with the public about the state of handing this world over to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, t-shirts, bags and key rings against the end of the world, with which people can also support us through www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap, along with other performers, also recorded the so-called anthem against the doom of the world entitled "The Doom of the World falls out".
The anthem on YouTube is already very popular today. Will it also be performed at the benefit concerts?
Of course, at the very end, provided that everything works and the end of the world does not take place...
The anthem is to be sung by all performers at all three concerts at the same time.
In addition, the hymns will be broadcast live together in a direct connection from Czech television.
The lyrics of the anthem are by Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, also Xindl X sings with...
How did you come to work with both of them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is due to the fact that we realize many charity events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
This has shown that most are interested in working with us, and have fun with it.
To what end does the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world benefit?
For the establishment of the barrier-free education centre Studeo, which we have been working on for six years together with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
Students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the editors, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building is to be built, into which we then move in with this project.
Several groups and performers perform at each concert.
What criteria did you choose these according to?
We wanted to put together a program that would appeal to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere perform with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý.
You can find everything else on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "large events" also planned for the future?
In May we perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and also for this concert we prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are in the USA - would also like to combine this with appearances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have already appeared in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group composed of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first sight.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs have to be transported in the luggage compartment. We also have to carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that sometimes I have already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travel abroad you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than with us, we witnessed in Russia that everything is still in its beginnings in the East.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not wheelchair accessible. There it is still unusual when someone is travelling in a wheelchair alone in the city centre.
It is not even natural there to leave a wheelchair user in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There's a lot of things we're stuck in after...
It should be noted, however, that improving the situation always depends on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
However, it is not exactly common for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in the social events there, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is very popular at the moment, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intense.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone, among other things, I founded a music company together with a colleague.
Well, and with time, as our presenter, L’a Angelovič, tends to say, something is out of control (laughs).
But the band only became known in recent years, or am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us; we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and you cannot see it outwardly, your own performance does not exist in a sense.
Thanks to EU funding, we can also afford good proofreaders, high-quality equipment and the like.
Was it your goal to get it this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential that things could be dealt with differently.
In show business, one often copies the other today.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and accepted only after a long time.
There are only a few really unique things, and I dare say that tap tap is one of them.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is, of course, pity; this is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we need to regret.
It is people who can live and develop a full life if they have the means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed something, it is not just progress for themselves, but for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something well, you must not compromise on many things and must also demand a certain discipline.
However, I think that this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic performances, and when they find out that they have to test twice a week, take preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, the enthusiasm of many quickly fades out.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: L’a Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come and go, you can't stop that.
Whoever has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
