Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papilomaviruses, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Creep lice and scabies are among the parasitic STIs.
Who are the main groups concerned?
Syphilis and trippers are mainly found in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute expects at least four out of five of all syphilis cases reported in Germany to be transmitted through sexual contacts between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonaden, candidiasis (fungal), trippers and human papilomaviruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The spread of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is comparatively low - nevertheless: about 20 percent of the HIV new infections belong to this group.
Chlamydia infections are much more common among adolescents than among other populations.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15-25.
Human papilomaviruses are also common in adolescents in this country.
How has the number of infections developed?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections more than doubled from 1697 diseases in 2001 to 3698 diseases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has decreased since 2007.
In 2011, there were around 2700 cases.
That's about a tenth less than the year before.
What are the symptoms of venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause genital ulcers, urination, discharge, abdominal pain, blisters or warts.
Often, however, they do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of contagion, but do not provide 100% protection.
Because in some cases pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through lubrication infections and close body contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations especially in frequently changing sex partners.
Most STIs can be treated early and late consequences can be avoided.
