Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces difficult start
While Mexico's future President Enrique Pena Nieto is preparing to take office, Will Grant of the BBC analyses the challenges and mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly poor.
Even on better days, this is an ever-congested city, but on Monday, a steel ring was built that shuts down several important transport routes to the capital and causes chaos on the streets.
The aim, however, was not to disturb commuters on their way to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching Parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will be given the presidency and take over the leadership of the nation.
He is facing a complex task.
Under the divisive government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has been able to prove itself economically well, but the country is under the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
"My government is strongly committed to reducing violence," Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before going on an equal footing with the U.S. president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, sprawling part of the country surrounding the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A Direct Man
For example, in the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, people like to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute to it the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, one can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto had built and which represent a great improvement over the fragile, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques with its name also hang outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect him to make real and lasting changes," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the Pena Nietos party, PRI.
In particular, as far as security and the economy are concerned, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so desperately needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
