Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I am Tory
Not only university students of today are attacked for their views
It had always been my greatest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended the university that I once thought was the world's greatest scientific stamp, a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization - free thinking and tolerance.
But within two weeks of my entry into Worscester College at the end of the eighties - there I had intended to study history - I had packed my suitcases again and thus caused the first scandal of my life.
My father broke into tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I left because I had a problem with fellow students having sex in the adjacent room.
Author A N Wilson said mischievously that I had left university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
But the truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I did, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I had come from a private school.
I had only been harassed for one reason - a reason that seemed so narrow and cruel in this alleged cradle of enlightenment: My now deceased father Woodrow Wyatt had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I support the Conservative Party.
Why do I mention this right now?
Well, according to recent reports, a new generation of moderate right-wing students suffer similar persecution.
The organized and increasing hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that one group of them last week called for the same equality protection that benefits gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's Junior Common Room (JCR) state that they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared undesirable" due to their political views.
They demand a place on their college's equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be expressed freely.
Their situation was aggravated by a recent documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which portrayed Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
It featured, among others, graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Conservative Student Association of the University of Oxford, who drove in a Rolls-Royce and boasted with silver-coloured suit and silver-covered walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are considered to be "sins for the introduction of higher tuition fees".
20-year-old Luke Black, Vice President of the Conservative Student Association of Nottingham University, said in a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing leftist tendency at universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know each other".
Samuel Roberts, 21 and History student in Corpus Christi, who initiated the application for greater protection, believes such a climate is "unpleasant." 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, President-elect of the Conservative Student Association of Oxford, says she has observed a growing rejection of JCR members against students of the moderate right.
"This is a danger to intellectual discourse and the well-being of members," she says.
In my first weeks in Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I had arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
In the previous year, the university had voted not to award an honorary title to Margaret Thatcher - a former student - due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would even have made Stalinists startle.
In the first days of the freshman week, when new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of the future events.
I had the experience that the tutors not only tolerated the mockery of Tory students, but even participated with pleasure.
Political issues such as the miners strike, privatization and the rejection of the government of sanctions against the apartheid regime of South Africa found their way into the wooden paneled rooms of the tutorial.
At the first of these events, I was supposed to translate French texts from the 18th century into English. I had not been aware of what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and pretty ugly.
"Do Thatcher supporters grow up learning French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students giggled.
My eyes were filled with tears.
"I suggest that you take a few French lessons in your spare time - so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt growled to me.
I returned to my room with my head hanging.
That night, I was sitting alone at dinner in college when someone lightly tapped me on the shoulder.
It was an English student from the second year named James who introduced himself as a member of the conservative student association.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it's what it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory is being harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be worse for you.
Most Tory freshmen pretend to be supporters of the Labour Party.
In a local pub, I later tried to disguise myself.
I insisted that I didn't agree with Mrs. Thatcher on all points.
This trick should prove to be unsuccessful.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and economics, who ironically had attended Eton College, considered conservative, said to me, "You are the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was pervert and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" someone asked me.
They're hitting each other, aren't they?
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever succeed in living a normal life at the University of Oxford?
Would I not be able to meet like-minded people until after dark?
Should I have to turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that lay ahead of me stretched before my spiritual eye to a purgatory of contempt and isolation.
The only tutor who openly identified himself as Tory was Norman Stone, professor of contemporary history who had his seat in my college.
He was hated not only for being a Conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for them.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty, and rejected it for its Marxist-Determinist historical perspective.
In 1997 he took up a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I began to commute between Oxford and my parents' house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford, and why I did it.
He seemed unbelieving.
During his time in the Forties, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said.
They would never do such a thing, not in my city of dreamy tower peaks.
Even my Communist friends always displayed impeccable manners.
His wet eyes clouded.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure you're just being teased.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also Tory supporters, had yielded to the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, in which another historian had seriously claimed that I was "an enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Although I secretly went to pieces of shame, I admitted that my parents had subjected me to "brainwashing," calling them "old fools."
The relief lasted only a short time.
It was my father who punched the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my bunnies gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You're welcome to call me a whiny limp dick.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer from such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic is that it was Oxford - a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
