This is only for the Internet, so we had to make it funny and funny.
This is the biggest problem in this country.
When planting we are the worst in the world, so we realized that it was a subject that we had to take care of.
We knew that the government had tried a lot, such as the marketing of perfume with pheromones or the organization of speed dating evenings (fast flirts).
It is possible that many of these ideas were creative, but they did not necessarily lead to success.
So we thought, why don't we do something as creative as possible to tackle this problem, such as composing a rap?
1.2 children
Those who do not take this issue lightly are the government of Singapore.
Each year, it spends $1,300 on policy measures to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for married couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But everything has had little success so far.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its national population authority, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was over 2 - which is also known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't the Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Authority, says this is due to "better education" and "greater career opportunities".
"This has enabled people to have much more options in terms of life goals and to set priorities other than getting married and making a family," she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the increase in the number of singles and the delaying of marriage and births, the result of which is the reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at a sharp increase in immigration in order to counteract the reduction of the population led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where the barely concealed xenophobia against many new immigrants is flourishing, especially against the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also considered to be one of the reasons that the Singapore ruling party achieved its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While the falling birth rate has the known impact on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, health costs, and immigration policies, the Singapore example also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to ensure that not so many small apartments are built.
It has already had an impact on the housing market.
The Urban Development Authority has begun to control the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living space of 46 square meters and show a great sales success.
However, there is concern that they can promote the lifestyle of the single, and that they discourage construction companies from building large homes for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, Director General of the real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoe boxes" can be sold much faster than larger housing units.
They are so popular, and the units are sold out by days and even weeks faster than the larger housing units.
This means that they are much better for our cash flow.
He admits, however, that the new standards give developers clearer orientations, which were previously hampered if they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for an increase in the national birth rate, the talks with the Singaporeans working in the financial district show that they will not have a major impact.
"People are very stressed, the housing and education are expensive, which is why many put it off," says a young manager.
The children can have others.
"It's important for me to have my own money and time," says another man, about twenty years old.
Men and women point to their careers, stress and costs of ownership and education as reasons why they cannot have children.
That is why the Singaporeans have the last word when it comes to having children - there is so much the government can do.
The offline private offline is private online
Privacy
According to the dictionary, this is the property of private or "that area of private life where one is entitled to protection from any kind of interference".
What's private for someone under the age of 16?
How is this definition applied to his everyday life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he faces when he makes known on the Internet situations he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15 who are often on the Internet.
In four of the cases, they linked the term to "somewhat very own" on a personal level and "to the password and the user" when applying it to social networks.
"I wouldn't disclose my deepest secrets in a post," says 10-year-old Jorge while trying to explain the meaning of "private" in websites such as Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother is allowed to know them, but not the whole world," he confirms.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures of games.
I also spend my time with acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that's not mine, or someone who makes the fool," he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, nudes, crimes, or offensive or violent comments.
Jorge assures to know 35 friends he has in FB and nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I registered on Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone answers me, I'm just uploading it," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can talk quickly to relatives in the distance or with friends," he says.
When asked, he answers that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown.
Even if someone were to recommend a stranger to him, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask, he admits not to know 20 of the people he has added to his friend list.
"That doesn't scare me because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to the boy, no one has made any suggestions or asked him for his address or phone number.
"If someone pushes me or demands them from me, I simply remove them from my user account," he admits.
José contacted Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unknown to experiences known today as cyberbullying.
A friend's acquaintance was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was," he assures.
According to José, the victim didn't close the account.
"He only did it privately."
He then explains a number of steps to configure a user account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, that's what I'd do if he was unsympathetic or if I wanted to wipe him out.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, teacher of English with a university degree in education and learning, believes that in order to orient the children and young people, it must be understood that it is the purpose of social networks to inform.
"The Internet emerged as a medium for the search for information; with the publication of these pages, the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that the academic Marc Prensky, holder of a master's degree in pedagogy at Yale University and author of the work "Digital Natives and Immigrants", formed these terms to explain the phenomenon.
They are the digital natives, the children and young people who grew up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants they are supposed to teach while we are still learning," he says.
He explains that this is a complex issue, "because we require them to have a defined criterion on what can be disseminated, published or said, at an age where maturity is not sufficient."
"They should also be selective if they want to be popular, have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents what privacy is is to ask them questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do it doesn't work," he says.
Porras then calls some possibilities: there are things you wouldn't tell a stranger. Then why do you do it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like to publish a photo of you, like the one you published from a friend?
Do you know what the others publish about you?
Did you ask the other people for permission before you labeled photos of celebrations?
And one more question: Does everyone need to know what you're doing at any moment?
Another point is to give them to understand that they need to act online as they do offline.
They're the same rules.
"Someone outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks," he explains.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educator, comments that it is essential for parents to carefully read the guidelines of social networks.
When they understand all sections, they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, age, or what you can share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children must be reminded of the lesson "Don't talk to strangers".
Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was theoretically to be signed by the seven governments present.
Efe repeatedly attempted to gain access to the signed document at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur. Sources in the State and President's Chancellery initially announced that they would hand it over after the cloister, but subsequently stated that it would be published at some time on the Peruvian government's website.
When asked about the text, they stated that the contents were presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information on the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only the image of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulating among journalists was received by the press officers of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, causing discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the President of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but this was the Humala Declaration and not the official document for the conclusion of the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South American - Arab Summit (ASPA), and the so-called Lima Declaration, which was previously announced, was also not published on this occasion, despite the press’s strong call.
On the official ASPA website, you can be sure that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems were in place for journalists, but to a large extent they restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of The Hague that resolves a border conflict between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the ICC, which began in The Hague on Monday, in the trial Lima initiated against Santiago to listen to the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the verdict on the differences we are currently making to this international court," said Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and remains a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to the international courts," Piñera adds and salutes Humala with a handshake against the flags of both countries.
Both presidents confirmed that they would submit to the ICJ, after Colombia had brought an action against the Bogotá Agreement after a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which considered it a serious mistake, agreeing to submit to the judgments of that international court.
The summit was attended by the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unasur since 2011 after the resignation of its President Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
Guest President Ollanta Humala opened the morning talks and ended the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The head of state read the final document, in which it announced that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set for a total investment of 17 billion dollars.
Regarding the decisions taken, he said that the Unasur countries "will take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, which is why we are extending the decisions on residence rights."
He announced that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised transnational crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act together and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant features, but rather serve to expand our output and show our peoples a better future," added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial connections in South America, especially in rural and border areas... thus uniting our countries and opening up new economic forms," the Peruvian President said in a read-out statement.
Among these projects would also be five Peruvians, who would be on the cross axes of his area from the coast to Brazil, and two of which would provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he did not give any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and good neighbourly relations was another aspect highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before beginning his participation in the regional meeting that on Saturday in Mexico he expected a meeting with his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, in order to treat the maritime conflict respectfully after a verdict of the ICC challenged by Bogotá.
"Maybe tomorrow (Saturday) I will meet President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary," he underlined.
"I hope to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectfully as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the inauguration of the new President of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc also met in advance to adopt the 2013 plan of action to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter is currently excluded.
Peru presides over the time of the regional bloc.
