The President of Ecuador also considers the wish of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to be "absolutely entitled" to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries, now and after the ruling of the International Court of Justice of The Hague, which favoured the maritime sovereignty of Nicaragua.
At present, this judgment is not being implemented.
It is a problem between a South American and a Central American state.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome in the pursuit of a common path.
They must be comprehensively treated so that they can be overcome and looked forward.
He also relied on a good conclusion of the disputes over the maritime borders between Peru and Chile before the same court, saying that "it is right for Latin America to appeal to international authorities if both countries commit themselves to accepting the judgment, even if it is very hard."
With regard to the possibility of standing as a candidate for the next presidential election in Ecuador to achieve his third consecutive mandate, he stated that he saw this opportunity "with much optimism and joy, although sometimes it is very difficult."
Correa assured that if he lost the February 2013 elections, he would retire from political life.
I have never personally been interested in power, but under such unjust circumstances as in Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement had the belief that it was I who guaranteed this probable victory, so I have to meet this responsibility," he said.
If I were to win, it would be my last period as president, after which I withdraw from public life.
This also applies if we lose.
"That's decided," he explained.
Correa also referred to the treatment of the health problems of the President of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, in Cuba.
I have just spoken to Vice-President of Venezuela Nicolás Maduro, who told me that he had travelled there for a planned routine treatment and that he would be expected to be able to return to Cuba after the election campaign.
