The cause of death because of AIDS is now too late to recognize
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed with the results of the investigation: HIV positive.
"It was as if a bomb hit," he says about the moment he received the diagnosis that the doctor "tryed to weaken" without any apparent success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to learn about it; and this with such commitment that he was celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), in which he came after several fights in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was difficult to imagine in the early 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmata.
At the time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because it led to a dead end."
At that time AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today it is possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who know nothing about their disease and where the virus has already done harm and exhausted their immune system, and who are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the occurrence of the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who receives the treatment in time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of HCG's HIV unit, saying that this information was supported by a prestigious scientific publication in April of this year.
The expert on infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, the scientists concluded that AIDS was not a death sentence, but that the years of survival and quality of life depended on the degree of impairment of the immune system of the individuals at the start of treatment, and that those more likely to be non-drug addicts were: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years with a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above remarks mean that those who receive the diagnosis HIV positive at the age of 25 can, in this sense, "beget 75 years of age without problems as long as they are under control," said this expert.
In order to correctly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Even if mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS has decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (ONUSIDA Annual Report), it is still true that 60 percent of patients registered in the national database have died since the release of AIDS.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by the month of May of this year there are already 187 deaths; however, it is assured that universal access to antiretroviral medicines has been available since 2005.
- So why are people still dying from it?
- In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is our hospital.
At least in the past 12 years, we have not had any drug supply problems. The problem is that people come in a very advanced state because they do not know their condition of infection, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have an accompanying infection. In order to be able to influence global mortality, more early diagnoses are required, which is why all people who require this need massive detection tests."
The experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee on AIDS Prevention in Jalisco) and also the patients such as Fabrizio, who had his test carried out at a private laboratory, for the sole reason that it had made a friend of him who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had the Kaposi sarcoma (a cancer-like tumor), which is one of the usual complications.
Everything's different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die and don't want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I prefer to burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was to improve, I feed well, exercise and take the medication.
Today, all his parents know is that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, do a lot of work, have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO to animate with his testimony those who are afraid today in the context of the worldwide AIDS day.
They should take the test if they belong to the risk group. The sooner they know whether they are HIV positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big holes between the health programmes and the ordinary citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, journalist from Guadalajara, who has taken care of the cause of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the designated places, "the distribution of condoms has actually been increased; in the past they were delivered individually, now they give us packages with a hundred pieces, which is good, but there are still people who have no access to a condom," he said.
Young people are at risk for new infections.
"What do you need it for?" is a widespread mockery question of social workers, orientation staff in schools, employees in pharmacies and in the health care system, which young people do not want to expose themselves to, the correspondent assured.
He proposed to reorient this inefficient distribution; the condoms should be located not only behind the counter, but in public toilets of facilities frequently visited by young people.
Promiscuity should not be promoted.
They are not to be paid for the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González replied to the question whether there would be a distribution of preservatives under his administration.
"Sexuality does not look like this; it is best to bring the condoms closer to those who already engage in sexual activity," he put it to the point.
Key Jalisco figures
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state is nationally ranked 4th in new and cumulated AIDS cases, and 13th in terms of HIV.
92% of the infections are caused by sexual intercourse, 6% by blood and 2% by perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because for each registered case there are 4 or 5 people who do not know.
After the United States Court of Appeal has confirmed a verdict that does not recognise the restructuring of the Vitro Group's liabilities achieved through a trade dispute in Mexico, an ominous precedent will be created for any national company with branches in the neighbouring country that has payment problems.
